<div id="review_2297928060" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2297928060" />
    <a title="Noah Goats" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41735508-noah-goats"><img alt="Noah Goats" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1526489093p2/41735508.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2297928060?book_show_action=true">Feb 22, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Noah Goats" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Noah Goats" href="/user/show/41735508-noah-goats">Noah Goats</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2297928060" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17201031450363657806">According to Hume, Rousseau was “a monster who saw himself as the only important being in the universe,” and as I read this book it soon became clear that the same could be said about most of our public intellectuals, or at least the ones Paul Johnson has chosen to profile here.<br/><br/>This collection of biographical essays is a series of brutal hatchet jobs where Johnson briefly praises the achievements of these famous minds before getting down to what he really wants to talk about: what terrible, self</span>
  <span id="freeText17201031450363657806" style="display:none">According to Hume, Rousseau was “a monster who saw himself as the only important being in the universe,” and as I read this book it soon became clear that the same could be said about most of our public intellectuals, or at least the ones Paul Johnson has chosen to profile here.<br /><br />This collection of biographical essays is a series of brutal hatchet jobs where Johnson briefly praises the achievements of these famous minds before getting down to what he really wants to talk about: what terrible, selfish, egocentric, hypocritical monsters they all were. <br /><br />Johnson’s thesis is that intellectuals are, to borrow a phrase from Dr Kelso, “bastard coated bastards with bastard filling,” and we should hesitate before allowing ourselves to be guided by the ideas of such towering hypocrites. But in his selection of intellectuals for this book Johnson put a heavy thumb down on the scale in favor of his argument. If, for example, he had chosen to profile George Orwell instead of his publisher, Victor Gollancz, he would have written about a vastly more important intellectual. But because Orwell was not a bastard coated bastard with bastard filling Johnson would have undermined his thesis by writing about him. Gollancz is one of a handful of people profiled here don’t fit in with the other greats (does anyone read Edmund Wilson anymore?) and you should take this cherry picking into account as you read this book.<br /><br />There was also a sort of repetitiveness in these biographical sketches, especially in regard to the sexual pacadillos (and occasional pecadotes) committed by these intellectuals. At some point the long laundry lists of infidelities blur together. Johnson’s obsession with the sexual lives of his subjects sometimes smacks of titillated puritanism. <br /><br />Johnson clearly has a fairly conservative worldview and has only chosen leftists and liberals for his attacks. This is perhaps excusable since intellectuals are mostly left of center, but I’m sure he could have found at least a couple token conservatives to throw under the bus if he had tried.<br /><br />Still, Johnson has written vivid and fascinating portraits of these (mostly) important writers, philosophers, and thinkers, and I enjoyed this book very much.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17201031450363657806" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

