<div id="review_3081572067" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3081572067" />
    <a title="Adam Glantz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/711453-adam-glantz"><img alt="Adam Glantz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1362284036p2/711453.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3081572067?book_show_action=true">Dec 24, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam Glantz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam Glantz" href="/user/show/711453-adam-glantz">Adam Glantz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/8205107-intellectuals">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3081572067" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6412112413386561712">As will be no surprise to anyone who&apos;s gone a chapter or two in the book, this is a Burkean conservative critique of intellectuals, defined as creative people of the Enlightenment and beyond, who took over from (and worked in opposition to) religious divines in the task of seeking to promote the best human society possible, this time using their own reason and example. The author&apos;s justifiable response is to probe that example to determine if intellectuals merit their claim to authority.<br/><br/>The answ</span>
  <span id="freeText6412112413386561712" style="display:none">As will be no surprise to anyone who's gone a chapter or two in the book, this is a Burkean conservative critique of intellectuals, defined as creative people of the Enlightenment and beyond, who took over from (and worked in opposition to) religious divines in the task of seeking to promote the best human society possible, this time using their own reason and example. The author's justifiable response is to probe that example to determine if intellectuals merit their claim to authority.<br /><br />The answer is resounding: they do not. To one degree or another, they're all found lacking in their personal lives, which are usually a record of lying, philandering, hypocrisy, selfishness, arrogance, sexual dysfunction, and apologia for authoritarianism and violence. Some (Edmund Wilson, George Orwell, Cyril Connelly, and Evelyn Waugh) became, or remained, modest "men of letters," without pretensions, and are rewarded by Johnson's implicit favor. Others are not so lucky and three, Marx, Engels, and Brecht, are charlatans with no redeeming features.<br /><br />Ultimately, to the author, the problem with intellectuals isn't so much hubris and rushing in where angels fear to tread as it is promoting ideas at the expense of real human beings. This approach makes them the precursors and apologists for totalitarian regimes that attempt to remake whole societies, inevitably by terror and force. The conclusion is literally: beware of intellectuals.<br /><br />There are two potential vulnerabilities here. One is the possibility that Johnson has narrowed his definition of intellectuals, then cherry-picked his examples to fit it. I perceived this when he cites Byron and Camus as unobjectionable thinking men of action, but failed to follow up on them. A second is that when you accuse someone of lying, your proof must be genuine or else the argument falls apart...and I haven't checked Johnson's sources yet. But with the proviso of those hypotheticals, the thrust of his argument seems sound even for the non-conservative reader.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6412112413386561712" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

