    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_115547376" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/115547376" />
    <a title="Roger" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2004307-roger"><img alt="Roger" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422575991p2/2004307.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/115547376?book_show_action=true">Aug 06, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Roger" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Roger" href="/user/show/2004307-roger">Roger</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2004307-roger?shelf=philosophy-and-ideas">philosophy-and-ideas</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer115547376" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer48160083367581594">A series of biographies of famous intellectuals showing how they are not trustworthy or reliable. It is likely to provoke strong reactions from most readers, either positive or negative. It starts with Rousseau, Shelley, Marx, Tolstoy and carries well into the 20th century. The book does not develop a thesis, rather the thesis is unstated and obviously shapes the choice of material. I felt that much of the material was strongly slanted to the negative. It got even a little depressing at times to</span>
  <span id="freeText48160083367581594" style="display:none">A series of biographies of famous intellectuals showing how they are not trustworthy or reliable. It is likely to provoke strong reactions from most readers, either positive or negative. It starts with Rousseau, Shelley, Marx, Tolstoy and carries well into the 20th century. The book does not develop a thesis, rather the thesis is unstated and obviously shapes the choice of material. I felt that much of the material was strongly slanted to the negative. It got even a little depressing at times to read about the inexcusable behavior of such luminaries as Jean Paul Sartre. But I am not surprised that there was plenty of dirt to dig, and I personally buy in to the basic premise that being gifted and intelligent does not invest a person with the right to teach and lead the public, or culture, or opinion, particularly when their personal lives are disasters.<br /><br />To carry the implicit thesis a bit further, being great at writing novels, plays, philosophy, music or whatever is irrelevant to being qualified as a guide in other areas. But those who disregard this limitation are precisly the least trustworthy, because their arrogance makes them blind to the truth and lacking in compassion for others. Those who advocate universal charity and compassion and seek to tell everyone else how to behave often are despicable to those around them. This despicable behavior is set forth here in startling detail. Don't be surprised if the bubble of at least one of your intellectual heroes is burst.<br /><br />The point was made in this book, but I would have enjoyed a more balanced account of the lives of the subjects. Even a scoundrel like Brecht must have had more interesting and good traits to talk about. <br /><br />I was especially interested in the last chapter that covered another six or eight intellectuals and wound up with a discussion of Noam Chomsky's contradictory views of the atrocities of the United States in Vietnam and of the Pol Pot regime in Cambodia. The USA has made its mistakes, but the government can not be credibly accused of pursuing the single minded brutality of certain mostly communist regimes that are perversely celebrated by the same intellectuals who castiagate the US. I suppose consistency is too much to ask for.</span>
  <a data-text-id="48160083367581594" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

