  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1080164728" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1080164728" />
    <a title="Mike" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27986103-mike"><img alt="Mike" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1441940772p2/27986103.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1080164728?book_show_action=true">Oct 14, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mike" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mike" href="/user/show/27986103-mike">Mike</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/21300354-intellectuals">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1080164728" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer153073508715454210">One of a number of questions Johnson asks about intellectuals is this: <br/>&apos;...the [Lillian] Hellman case raises and important general question: to what extent do intellectuals as a class expect and require truth from those they admire?&apos;<br/>Apparently they expect little in the way of truth since the intellectuals Johnson discusses in detail in this book are almost to a class, liars. If they&apos;re not lying about their own histories (most of them seem to rewrite their family histories, and often much of wha</span>
  <span id="freeText153073508715454210" style="display:none">One of a number of questions Johnson asks about intellectuals is this: <br />'...the [Lillian] Hellman case raises and important general question: to what extent do intellectuals as a class expect and require truth from those they admire?'<br />Apparently they expect little in the way of truth since the intellectuals Johnson discusses in detail in this book are almost to a class, liars. If they're not lying about their own histories (most of them seem to rewrite their family histories, and often much of what they've done as well) they're lying about their circumstances, about their love lives (wives and mistresses, or lovers, in combination, but often hidden from each other), their financial state (an unwillingness to pay bills, repay loans, pay taxes is common to nearly all of them).<br />Anger is another feature, which leads to violence (including towards family and friends), which leads towards a kind of delight in murder. Marx may not have been personally responsible for any murders, but his followers certainly have been, and others in the book often see little problem with murdering people they don't like, or who are not worthy of living.<br />Then there is their attitude towards their children. Often they're ignored - in some cases, like Rousseau's, they were sent to orphanages almost as soon as they were born. Supposedly he never even named them. <br />It's hard to know where to stop. These people exemplify that puffed up and vain view of themselves which is the opposite extreme to humility. They want to change the world, but don't give a hoot about people actually living in the same household, or their neighbours, or friends. <br />And the end result for most of them is isolation, even madness. Alcoholism, drugs, debauchery and much more all play a common part amongst these people. <br />The biggest warning the book gives, perhaps, is that it's worth taking the thoughts of 'great' intellectuals with several grains of salt. Be very wary of becoming their disciples. </span>
  <a data-text-id="153073508715454210" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

