    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_269498445" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/269498445" />
    <a title="Bob" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/82944-bob"><img alt="Bob" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1502065904p2/82944.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/269498445?book_show_action=true">Jan 29, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bob" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bob" href="/user/show/82944-bob">Bob</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer269498445" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15318153634225249357">I was prompted to re-read this after the Shelley biography, since Johnson bases his chapter in this largely on Holmes. The premise, you may know, is a chapter each on a sequence of literary and philosophical figures who presumed to tell society how to restructure itself and a look at whether the way they conducted their own lives was in accordance with their principles.<br/>You won&apos;t be too surprised to hear that it often wasn&apos;t though a few of the lesser 20th century figures seem guilty of no worse </span>
  <span id="freeText15318153634225249357" style="display:none">I was prompted to re-read this after the Shelley biography, since Johnson bases his chapter in this largely on Holmes. The premise, you may know, is a chapter each on a sequence of literary and philosophical figures who presumed to tell society how to restructure itself and a look at whether the way they conducted their own lives was in accordance with their principles.<br />You won't be too surprised to hear that it often wasn't though a few of the lesser 20th century figures seem guilty of no worse an offense than failing to pay income taxes.<br />Additionally, I would generalize that even the most lauded and influential figures should not be held accountable for everything that came out of their mouths at age 19 and (with reference to Bertrand Russell), perhaps we should exclude "after the age of 88" as well.<br />Shelley however really was quite a cad with regard to abandoned and/or ignored wives, children and various other figures who trusted him with their reputations or livelihood. It is hard to cast oneself mentally back to a day when simply publishing doubts on the existence of God resulted in disgrace and imprisonment - Shelley's first offense, for which he was sent down from Oxford, estranged from his family and so on. [An hour after writing this, I have to laugh at myself - it is not necessary to cast one's mind further than just beyond the boundary of Europe, or to certain parts of the U.S., to risk punishment for atheism].<br />Johnson, a popular historian of very persuasive writing style and breadth of knowledge, is so deeply conservative and Christian that he blames the abandonment of faith for almost every modern ill, but any moral or ethical standard worth holding would probably not encompass most of the unfortunate conduct that he chronicles.<br />The chapter on Marx then propelled me to my next biography.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15318153634225249357" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


