    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1077049457" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1077049457" />
    <a title="Jacob Aitken" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5958504-jacob-aitken"><img alt="Jacob Aitken" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1463699884p2/5958504.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1077049457?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacob Aitken" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacob Aitken" href="/user/show/5958504-jacob-aitken">Jacob Aitken</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5958504-jacob-aitken?shelf=fighting-the-new-world-order">fighting-the-new-world-order</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5958504-jacob-aitken?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1077049457" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16853059325794796887">Sure, Johnson has an axe to grind, but facts are facts. His thesis is simple: the aforementioned avant-garde thinkers, so beloved of the Left today, championed the &quot;ideal&quot; of humanity while despising the particular person.<br/><br/>Rousseau: fathered numerous illegitimate children and shipped them off to different orphanages, where Johnson speculates they likely died of neglect. And Rousseau&apos;s commitment to the abstract is consistent: if one interprets &quot;the general will&quot; and the &quot;contrat social&quot; in terms </span>
  <span id="freeText16853059325794796887" style="display:none">Sure, Johnson has an axe to grind, but facts are facts. His thesis is simple: the aforementioned avant-garde thinkers, so beloved of the Left today, championed the "ideal" of humanity while despising the particular person.<br /><br />Rousseau: fathered numerous illegitimate children and shipped them off to different orphanages, where Johnson speculates they likely died of neglect. And Rousseau's commitment to the abstract is consistent: if one interprets "the general will" and the "contrat social" in terms of some abstract will, then the result is totalitarianism for someone will have to interpret that will. (If one interprets it by concrete cultural norms, then perhaps it isn't too bad).<br /><br />Marx: Like Rousseau, he also fathered illegitimate children. Criticisms of Marx's personal life are well known and documented, so we can be brief. He lived off of a capitalist while attacking capitalism. Not much else to say.<br /><br />Tolstoy: Like the men above, he fathered illegitimate children, debauching many of his maids. But here is where it gets weird. He wrote about it in his journals and encouraged his wife to read them as a holistic exercise. His teachings, while noble, are hypocritical of his lifestyle. He encouraged poverty but never gave up his county. He preached chastity while debauching wenches. I like Tolstoy's novels, though, so I won't say more.<br /><br />Betrand Russell: Admittedly a genius in mathematics, he was a complete imbecile everywhere else. He debauched many men's wives. He later said he couldn't be anti-American because most of his wives came from America! A pacifist, he advocated nuking the USSR to prevent them from getting nukes.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16853059325794796887" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

